library(httr)
library(XML)
# We manually found the following link via the Web browser's Developer Tools in the Network tab.
# We found the json files

u = "https://static01.nyt.com/newsgraphics/2020/03/16/coronavirus-maps/a3c88fc852744c0bdb9ff9ee092cc5db785705d6/data/timeseries/en/USA.json"

tt = GET(u, verbose = TRUE)
tt = rawToChar(tt$content)

library(RJSONIO)
us = fromJSON(tt)


# The URL for the JSON changes each day. So today's URL, we want to find it in the current day's page.
# We get the top-level page

ny = htmlParse(GET("https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html?action=click&module=Top%20Stories&pgtype=Homepage"))

# Then we find the HTML elements that have an immediate child text node that contains the string USA.json.
js = xpathSApply(ny, "//*[contains(./text(), 'USA.json')]", xmlValue)

#These are <script> elements containing JavaScript, not JSON.
# But we can find the URL with a regular expression in these
u = gsub('.*"(https://[^"]+USA.json)".*', "\\1", js)
u = unique(u)
# There is only 1 URL repeated multiple times.

# So now we have these

tt = GET(u, verbose = TRUE, followlocation = TRUE)
tt = rawToChar(tt$content)
library(RJSONIO)
us = fromJSON(tt)
length(us$data)

save(us, file = "covid.RData") # data is saved in the form of RData to avoid unnecessary web scraping

Setting up the data

The data extracted from the New York Times is first transformed into a data frame with the following code. Only the counties from California are used in building the plots.

Interactive Trend Plot

A line plot consisting of all the trends from each county is plotted using ggplot. Note that in the process of building this ggplot object, I have added the highlight_key function from the plotly library for the purpose of interactive highlighting later on. The code used to create the ggplot object is shown below:

library(ggplot2)
library(plotly)
library(dplyr)
trendPlot = covidDataCal %>%
  highlight_key(~County) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = DailyCases, color = County, group = 1,
             text = paste("County: ", FullName, 
                          "\nDate: ", Date,
                          "\nDaily Cases: ", DailyCases,
                          "\nCum. Cases: ", CumCases, 
                          "\nDaily Deaths: ", DailyDeaths,
                          "\nCum. Deaths: ", CumDeaths,
                          "\n% Cases/Capita (Day): ", round(PercentCasesPerCapita, 4),
                          "\n% Deaths/Capita (Day):", round(PercentDeathsPerCapita, 4),sep = ""))) +
  geom_line() + 
  ggtitle("Covid-19 Cases in California by County") + ylab("Daily Cases")
trendPlot

After creating the ggplot object, the next step is to transform it into an interactive plot using plotly. Note that there were a few additional functions and parameters that I added to allow for higlighting and producing tooltips in the plot. Specifically, those function/parameters are:

  • tooltip = "text" in ggplotly(): This parameter is used to add the text specified in the ggplot object created from the previous code snippet.

  • highlight(): Highlights specific lines on hover by setting on = "plotly_hover". Undo highlights and returns to default by setting off = "plotly_doubleclick". An additional parameter persistent = getOption("persistent", TRUE) is set to allow for multiple highlighting.

  • layout(updatemenus = list()): Used to create buttons to toggle lines in the plot. The buttons created are Hide all and Show all.

# make plotly
trendPlot.plotly = ggplotly(trendPlot, tooltip = "text", dynamicTicks = TRUE) %>%
  highlight(on = "plotly_hover", off = "plotly_doubleclick", 
            persistent = getOption("persistent", TRUE)) %>%
  layout(updatemenus = list(
    list(type = "buttons",
         direction = "right",
         xanchor = "left",
         yanchor = "top",
         showactive = FALSE,
         x = 1,
         y = 1.2,
         buttons = list(
           list(method = "restyle",
                args = list("visible", "all"),
                label = "show all"),
           list(method = "restyle",
                args = list("visible", "legendonly"),
                label = "hide all")
         )
    )
  ))
trendPlot.plotly$sizingPolicy$browser$fill = FALSE
trendPlot.plotly

The resulting HTML ouput can be viewed in covidTrend.html.

Plotting map using ggplot

The following code is used to build the ggplot map that will subsequently be used to create the non-interactive COVID-19 map gif, and the interactive COVID-19 plotly map.

Some explanations:

  • map_data function from the maps library is used to obtained the longitude and latitude data of each counties in California. This is then joined with the covidDataCal data frame from a previous snippet.

  • Cumulative cases is not able to tell the viewer much about the COVID-19 cases in each county due to the extreme outlier which is Los Angeles. Hence, the number of cases per 10,000 people is displayed instead.

  • An important parameter in this ggplot is the frame = Date parameter as it helps us navigate the number of cases for each day in the interactive plot and gif later on.

library(maps)
# join covidDataCal with mapCounty
calCountyMap = map_data('county', 'california')
calCountyMap$subregion = stringr::str_to_title(calCountyMap$subregion)
plotData = inner_join(calCountyMap, covidDataCal, by = c("subregion" = "County"))

# make the ggplot
options(scipen = 10)
plotData$Date = as.factor(plotData$Date)
plotData$casesPer10k = plotData$CumCases/plotData$Population*10000
covidMap = ggplot(data = plotData, aes(frame = Date, 
                                      text = paste("County: ", FullName, 
                                                "\nDate: ", Date,
                                                "\nCase/10k Pop.: ", casesPer10k,
                                                "\nDaily Cases: ", DailyCases,
                                                "\nCum. Cases: ", CumCases, 
                                                "\nDaily Deaths: ", DailyDeaths,
                                                "\nCum. Deaths: ", CumDeaths,
                                                "\n% Cases/Capita (Day): ", round(PercentCasesPerCapita, 4),
                                                "\n% Deaths/Capita (Day):", round(PercentDeathsPerCapita, 4),sep = ""))) + 
  geom_polygon(aes(x=long, y = lat, fill=casesPer10k, group = group), color="black") + 
  geom_text(aes(y=40, x=-116, label=as.Date(Date)), check_overlap = TRUE, size=4, fontface="bold") +
  lims(x = c(-125, -114), y = c(32,42.5)) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = rev(heat.colors(10)), na.value="grey80") +
  labs(title="Rate of COVID-19 Cases", x = "longitude", y = "latitude", fill = "Cases Per 10k Pop.")

Non-interactive COVID-19 Map gif

The gif is created using the gganimate and gifski.

  • transition_manual is used to create the color transitions ofthe cases per 10,000 people in the gif.

  • animate is used to produce the gif animation. The duration and fps parameters are set to denote the length of the gif and speed of date transitions. The gifski_renderer() is required for later versions of gganimate, according to some StackOverflow results.

# gif of covid map
library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
animatedMap <- covidMap +
  transition_manual(Date)
# get plot in GIF
mapGIF = animate(animatedMap, duration = 10, fps = 30, width = 500, height = 500, renderer = gifski_renderer())
# display gif
mapGIF
# save gif
anim_save("covidCal.gif", animation=mapGIF)

The resulting gif is shown below.

Interactive COVID-19 Map

The code used to created the interactive COVID-19 map using plotly might seem very simple and straightforward below, and that is due to all the required settings have already been computed in the process of building the ggplot map.

I had initially tried creating the plotly object by adding functions and parameters using the layout() and add_trace() functions, which did work in certain ways, but somehow produced bugs in certain other areas. This was fixed by using the frame = Date parameter in creating the ggplot map instead of dealing with the plotly functions here, as mentioned in a previous section.

# make interactive plot using plotly
covidMap.plotly = ggplotly(covidMap, tooltip = "text")
covidMap.plotly
saveWidget(covidMap.plotly, "covidMap.html", selfcontained = FALSE, title = "Covid-19 Cases by California Counties")

The result is the attached file covidMap.html.
